04539nam a22005775i 9780773598966DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20162016xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735989667 a10.1515/97807735989662doi  a(DE-B1597)657198  a(OCoLC)965343837  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a305.4qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aSmith-Prei, Carrie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAwkward Politics :bTechnologies of Popfeminist Activism /cCarrie Smith-Prei. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource :b10 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAwkward Activism in the Digital Age -- tProcess as a Politics: Collaborative Research, Political Urgency, and Feminist Histories -- tFeminist Activisms and Local Contexts: Forms and Trajectories -- tAwkwardness as Popfeminist Craft: Staying with the Trouble -- tMovements, Circulations, Technologies: Awkwardness on the Move -- tThe Affects of Adolescent Aesthetics: Popfeminism in Film and Literature -- tOn the Contemporary: Materiality and Virality of Feminism from Mainstream to the Academy -- tTowards an Awkward Ethos: Conviviality, Joy, and Feminist Ethics -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe increased use of digital tools for political activism has triggered heated debates about the effectiveness of digital campaigns for political change and feminist causes. While technology’s immediacy and transnational reach have broadened the potential impact of activism, it has, at the same time, complicated the goals, materiality, and consumption of feminist actions. In Awkward Politics, Carrie Smith-Prei and Maria Stehle suggest that awkwardness offers a means of engaging with twenty-first century feminist activism by accounting for the uncertainty of popfeminist moments and movements, its sometimes illegible meanings, affects, and aesthetics. By investigating transnational media ranging from popfeminist performance art, music, street activism, blogs, and hashtags to literature, film, academic theory, and protests, the authors demonstrate that viewing activist art through the lens of awkwardness can yield a nuanced critique. By developing awkwardness into a theoretical tool for intervention, a key concept of feminist politics, and a moving target, this innovative study dramatically alters the ways in which we approach activism, its forms, movements, and effects. It also suggests a broad range of applicability, from social movements to the academy. Breaking new ground through the intersections of technology, consumerism, and the political in popfeminist work, Awkward Politics highlights the urgency of feminist politics and activism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminismxPolitical aspects. 0aFeminismxSocial aspects. 0aFéminismexAspect politique. 0aFéminismexAspect social. 0aSocial mediaxPolitical aspects. 0aTechnologiexAspect politique. 0aTechnologyxPolitical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311127380808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016z978311127630440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359896640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773598966423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773598966/original  a978-3-11-127380-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-127630-4  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles